Introduction¶

The data set that has been selected by me is Medical Appointment No Shows. I selected this data as I would like to understand patient behaviour and what results in they showing up or not showing up for appointments. Dataset variables seems to be self explanatory and the variables are PatientId, AppointmentID, Gender, ScheduledDay, AppointmentDay, Age, Neighbourhood, Scholarship, Hipertension, Diabetes, Alcoholism, Handcap, SMS_received, No-show

Questions I am trying to answer are:¶

  • Does Gender has any impact on patient to be with status Show / No-Show?
  • Does Age has any impact on patient to be with status Show / No-Show?
  • Is there any Age difference along with Gender difference with the status of Show / NoShow?

df['Scheduledday'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Scheduledday'])
df['scheduled_day'] = df['Scheduledday'].dt.day
df['scheduled_weekday'] = df['Scheduledday'].dt.dayofweek
df['scheduled_week'] = df['Scheduledday'].dt.week
df['scheduled_month'] = df['Scheduledday'].dt.month
df['scheduled_day_name'] = df['Scheduledday'].dt.day_name()

df['Appointmentday'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Appointmentday'])
df['appointment_day'] = df['Appointmentday'].dt.day
df['appointment_weekday'] = df['Appointmentday'].dt.dayofweek
df['appointment_week'] = df['Appointmentday'].dt.week

Visualizing the categorical features first.¶

In [22]:
#  Categorical Data
categorical_variables = ['Hypertension', 'Scholarship', 'Diabetes', 'Gender']

#  Categorical Data
i = 2  # no. of rows
j = 2  # no. of columns
k = 1  # plot counter

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(14,10))
colour = ['r', 'b', 'g', 'c']

for var in categorical_variables:
    plt.subplot(i, j, k)
    plt.title('{}'.format(var, i, j, k), fontweight="bold", fontsize = 22.0)
    ax = df[var].value_counts(normalize=True).plot.bar(fontsize = 15.0, color = colour[k-1])
    plt.ylabel('Count %')
    for p in ax.patches:
        ax.annotate(round(p.get_height(), 2), (p.get_x() * 1.005, p.get_height() * 1.005))
    k = k + 1

plt.show()
Observations: ~20% of patient records have Hypertension. ~10% of the patient records have scholarship. ~7% of patient recodrs have diabetes. ~35% patient instances are with male records.

Bi-variate Analysis¶

Target Variable vs Indepedent Categorical Variable¶

In [31]:
category_list = [ 'Scholarship', 'Diabetes', 'Gender', 'Alcoholism', 'Hypertension', 'Handicap']
for col in category_list:
    df1 = pd.crosstab(df[col],df['Noshow'])
    df1.div(df1.sum(1).astype(float), axis=0).plot(kind="bar", figsize=(8,4));
    plt.ylabel('Proportion')
    plt.title(col + ' vs Noshow');
Onservations: Patients who have scholarship have slightly more "NoShow" status Patients who have Diabetes have slightly less "NoShow" status Patients who have Hypertension have slightly less "NoShow" status Not much of difference in "NoShow" status for Gender and Alcholism data cuts Ptaients with Handicap category 4 have more "NoShow" status

We will try to answer following questions with the help of the data¶

1. Does Gender has any impact on patient to be with status Show / No-Show?¶

In [35]:
col = 'Gender'
df1 = pd.crosstab(df[col],df['Noshow'])
df1.div(df1.sum(1).astype(float), axis=0).plot(kind="bar", figsize=(8,4));
plt.title('Gender vs Noshow')

Limitations¶

The data has information only for April, May and June. If atleast full year data would have provided, we could identify some trends MoM.

If we had some way of reminding patients regarding appointments and would have captured that data, we could identify how many reminders are needed for patient to show up

Conclusions¶

Gender does not have much inluence in having the status with Show/No Show

The mean age group of patients with "No Show = Yes" is less than patients with "No Show = No"

Of those patients who have showed up for appointment, majority patients with age group 0-20 for Males and 20-40 for Females. Of those patients who did not showed up for appointment, majority patients with age group 0-20 for Males and 20-60 for Females.
